ries, according to where species live: on land or in coastal, pelagic, and deep ocean habitats. The fact that most species groups, from bacteria to whales, appear to follow similar biogeographic patterns of richness within these habitats points toward some underlying structuring principles. Based on empirical analyses of environmental correlates across these habitats, the authors combine aspects of neutral, metabolic, and niche theory into one unifying framework. Applying it to model terrestrial and marine realms, the authors demonstrate that a relatively simple theory that incorporates temperature and community size as driving variables is able to explain divergent patterns of species richness at a global scale. Integrating ecological and evolutionary perspectives, A Theory of Global Biodiversity yields surprising insights into the fundamental mechanisms that shape the distribution of life on our planet.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aBiodiversity. 7aSCIENCE / Life Sciences / Biological Diversity.2bisacsh  aPET.  aambient energy.  aambient temperature.  abiodiversity drivers.  abiodiversity hotspots.  abiodiversity loss.  abiodiversity patterns.  abiodiversity research.  abiodiversity.  abiogeographic patterns.  acoastal biodiversity.  acoastal habitat.  acommunity size.  adeep-sea biodiversity.  adeep-sea habitat.  aecological theory.  aempirical data.  aevolution.  aglobal biodiversity.  aglobal distribution.  aglobal patterns.  aglobal theory.  ahabitat.  amacroecological patterns.  amarine biodiversity.  amarine pelagic biodiversity.  ametabolic theory.  ametacommunity model.  aneutral theory.  aniche theory.  apelagic habitat.  apotential evapotranspiration.  aspatial metacommunity model.  aspecies diversity.  aspecies richness.  atemperat